TOOLKIT=$(PROGRAMFILES)\Civ4SDK\Microsoft Visual C++ Toolkit 2003
PSDK=$(PROGRAMFILES)\Civ4SDK\WindowsSDK
CIV4_PATH=$(PROGRAMFILES)\Steam\steamapps\common\Sid Meier's Civilization IV Beyond the Sword
#
# <!-- custom: codex change: Civ4Libs path can be any folder outside git if it contains Boost 1.32.0 and Python24. -->
# CIV4_LIB_INSTALL_PATH is not set here.
# Instead, it should be defined as a Windows environment variable.
# Example (permanent):
#   System Properties → Environment Variables → Add:
#     Name: CIV4_LIB_INSTALL_PATH
#     Value: C:\Program Files (x86)\Civ4Libs
# This is where Boost 1.32.0 and Python24 headers/libs must be placed.
#
# <!-- custom: note 1 also anyways etc: i have not renamed mod name to AdvCiv-SAS in compiler files and such as may cause unexpected errors and our mod is fundamentally based on advciv mod so name is close enough, but the DLL is generated based on our real source files not base advciv ones i mean, just i am careful in this case to rather not rename mod name in compiler files or and such settings at least as of now, may change this later or maybe not since runs fine and does not seem to cause issues if i am not mistaken but anyways etc -->
#
# <!-- custom: note 2 anyways etc: unrelated but i would highly recommend after compile to delete the all the entire content in the (adjust to you mod path) C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\Sid Meier's Civilization IV Beyond the Sword\Beyond the Sword\Mods\AdvCiv-SAS\CvGameCoreDLL\Project\temp_files\ folder, as if you don't, then the next compile will be a fastdep if i am not mistaken and this seems to cause weird issues ingame, see readme known issues in advciv-sas or your mod if it has this readme as well anyways etc, so by deleting the folder after compuile it will do a full compile next time not a fast one based on precompiled stuff stored from last compile if i am not mistaken and from little i know or noticed of it but anyways etc, hopefully helpful, but anyways etc. -->
